11-2-80 1

because for the person the ontological categories of the spatiotemporal world (time, space and causation) release their grip from him long enough for him to act freely for the first and only moment in his life. Thereby the great chain of determinism that connects all his splintered parts --parts of his true self-- that chain is broken, and something new has come into existence unforeseen at the beginning of creation. It is my belief that this abolishes what I call dead or false time (as in "He causes things to look different so it'd appear time has passed"), and into the vacuum left by the disappearance of false time rushes real time, live time, which is to say the genuine future. Therefore the grip of the past over him dissolves, and maybe it is the grip of the past that constitutes this "astral determinism or heimarmene," Whatever word you wish: the word or words used point to the person never being more than the sum total of all that has happened to him, which is to say, his personal history. And with the short-circuiting or burning up of his karma his punishment is also obviated, as when the messenger inserts the blank white sheet of paper instead of the person's bill of particulars into the retribution machine. This is the second birth or birth from above or birth in the Spirit of Christianity; it is also known to the Taoist alchemists and to the Western alchemists (to them, the chemical wedding, the hierogamy, marriage of the opposites). What strikes me about this is that it is cosmogenesis in miniature, in the microcosm, because something has come into being ex nihilo. What the person did --the heroic act-- he could not do given who he is, given his history, his karma. It is an impossibility. Thus in a real and literal sense a new self has been born in him, since this act, this deed, could not issue out of the old self, the self splintered throughout time and space. This is as much a miracle as the original cosmogenesis; in a sense it is the original cosmogenesis, and perhaps the ruah is present at it as it was in the beginning. So I felt as if another self had taken me over; my actions were "dissociated," without ideation; and then Thomas came into being in me. Maybe he was new, not a lost part rejoining me but new ex nihilo, the permanent offspring of the heroic deed that broke the power of the world-rule existentially. What world lost, self acquired. There is a quantum transfer of essence from world to self, so that the balance between the two shifts critically.


